@startuml
title Study App — deployment topology (what actually runs today)
$Subtitle("Three compose stacks on one host; no cloud production environment yet — honest by design")

top to bottom direction

actor "Developer /\nintegrator" as Dev

node "Docker host (laptop / stand)" as Host {

  package "app stack\n(docker-compose.yml)" as AppStack {
    [api\nFastAPI · Uvicorn\n:8000] as Api
    database "postgres\npostgres:16-alpine\nvolume ./var/postgres" as Pg
  }

  package "observability stack\n(docker-compose.observability.yml)" as ObsStack {
    [prometheus] as Prom
    [grafana] as Graf
    [blackbox-exporter] as Bbx
  }

  package "log stack\n(docker-compose.logging.yml)" as LogStack {
    [filebeat] as FB
    [elasticsearch 8.15] as ES
    [kibana] as Kib
  }

  [portal\nnginx-alpine\nstatic HTML] as Portal
}

cloud "GitHub" as GH {
  [Actions CI\nquality gates] as CI
  [Pages staging\nsync-staging] as Staging
}

Dev --> Api : HTTPS / JSON
Dev --> Portal : browse docs
Dev --> Graf : dashboards
Dev --> Kib : logs

Api --> Pg : SQL (psycopg3)
Prom ..> Api : scrape /metrics
Bbx ..> Api : probe /ready
Graf --> Prom
Api ..> FB : NDJSON log file
FB --> ES
Kib --> ES

CI ..> Portal : build gate (docs-check)
CI ..> Api : tests + openapi parity
Staging ..> Portal : published copy

note bottom of Pg
  Single instance, single volume.
  No replica, no automated backup yet
  (ADR 0037 follow-ups).
end note

note bottom of Host
  Blast radius: everything shares one host.
  Any stack can be down independently;
  only api+postgres are load-bearing for the product.
end note

@enduml
